SIMPLE: neptune
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Neptune
<hw>Nep"tune</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Neptunus</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Rom. Myth.)</fld> <def>The
son of Saturn and Ops, the god of the waters, especially of the sea. He
is represented as bearing a trident for a scepter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>The remotest major planet of
our solar system, discovered -- as a result of the computations of
<persfn>Leverrier</persfn>, of Paris -- by <persfn>Galle</persfn>, of
Berlin, September 23, 1846. It is classed as a <isa>gas giant</isa>, and
has a radius of 22,716 km and an estimated mass of 1.027 x
10<exp>26</exp> kg, with an average density of 2.27 g/cc. Its mean
distance from the sun is about 5,000,000,000 km (3,106,856,000 miles),
and its period of revolution is about 164.78 years.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Neptune powder</b></col>, <cd>an explosive containing
nitroglycerin, -- used in blasting.</cd> -- <col><b>Neptune's
cup</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a very large, cup-shaped, marine
sponge (<spn>Thalassema Neptuni</spn>).</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Neptunian</ent>⟦br⟧
